1/Beartooth_Highway_-_Pilot_and_Index_Peaks_-_NARA_-_7717230.jpg","cap":"Pilot and Index Peaks","desc":"These landmarks of the Beartooth Highway are immediately recognizable and dominate the scenery. Location: Montana (44.925° N 109.693° W) Status: Public domain. Photo by Katie Armstrong of NSBO","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Beartooth_Highway_-_Pilot_and_Index_Peaks_-_NARA_-_7717230.jpg"},{"url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/Beartooth_Highway_-_Pilot_and_Index_Peaks_-_NARA_-_7717264.jpg/1280px-Beartooth_Highway_-_Pilot_and_Index_Peaks_-_NARA_-_7717264.jpg","full":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/7/7e/Beartooth_Highway_-_Pilot_and_Index_Peaks_-_NARA_-_7717264.jpg","cap":"Pilot and Index Peaks","desc":"The Highway passes through geologically diverse environments. Shown here, Pilot and Index Peaks in the Absaroka Range are examples of mountains formed by volcanic processes, while the Beartooth Range is of granitic origin and represents some of the oldest rocks in the world. Location: Montana (44.926° N 109.688° W) Status: Public domain. Courtesy of U.S. Forest Service - Custer or Gallatin NF, MT","credit":"Public domain","pageUrl":"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Beartooth_Highway_-_Pilot_and_Index_Peaks_-_NARA_-_7717264.jpg"}]}